Canonical-trigger rule
======================

Relevant verifier rule from scripts/verify-pentagon-autonomy-from-logs.mjs:
  isCanonicalTrigger(trigger, expectedAgentId, expectedAgentMessageCounts)
  requires:
    trigger.claimed_at
    trigger.completed_at
    both timestamps parse
    claimed_at < completed_at
    at least one expected-agent message in the same conversation
    trigger.agent_id === expectedAgentId

resolveCanonicalAck then filters triggers by hash/tier/proof path and selects
the most recent canonical trigger by completed_at. If no canonical trigger
exists, it returns a failure detail with reason "no Maya ACK in canonical
trigger", trigger_rows, and candidate_trigger_ids.

Run 014 has exact ACK messages, but no original Maya-target trigger row for the
hash. Therefore the verifier rejection is correct. Loosening this rule would
hide the audit-chain defect.


Root-cause analysis
===================

Candidate a: Race condition where message arrives before trigger row commit.
  Possible but not the best fit. The missing row still did not exist after the
  full harness window and later audit. A commit-lag race should normally resolve
  into a durable row eventually.

Candidate b: Pentagon bug, trigger creation silently fails for certain inputs or timing.
  Best fit. Equivalent native instruction messages in the same conversation
  created triggers for runs 001-013. During run 014, later reverse and follow-up
  triggers were created normally in the same conversation. The only missing
  artifact is the original Theo -> Maya run-014 trigger row. Pentagon still
  processed the message through an alternate message-poller path and Maya
  replied, so the app saw the work but failed the durable trigger invariant.

Candidate c: Bridge race condition where the bridge created the trigger but it was deleted/moved.
  Not supported. The bridge does not create original trigger rows and existing
  trigger rows are durable in this schema; later queries show other rows remain.
  The runner had deliberately stopped the bridge for native activation probing.

Candidate d: Schema/permissions rejected the insert.
  Not strongly supported. It could be a hidden Pentagon-side insertion failure,
  but the same session/conversation created adjacent triggers before and after
  run 014. No broad RLS/schema outage is visible.

Candidate e: Something else.
  No stronger alternate mechanism was found. One environmental oddity is that
  the runner stops the bridge to force native activation, so the native app's
  message-poller path can do work without a bridge trigger. That explains why
  the ACK existed, but not why the original trigger row was never created.


